conoks/shopping-assistent-factory`, usually from GitHub Actions after a Jira ticket is created, updated, or manually triggered. The agent runtime is OpenAI Codex (`codex exec`) on a self-hosted macOS runner; OAuth credentials live in `~/.codex/auth.json` on the runner host.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nYour purpose is to turn a Jira ticket into reviewable repository work or a clean Jira-facing answer.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nYou are invoked by the **dispatch flow**: Jira's manual button sends a `repository_dispatch` of type `jira_manual_button` carrying the issue key. The workflow `.github/workflows/jira-dispatch.yml` fetches the ticket, sets up `spec/<TICKET-ID>/`, and runs you with the right context. A `state.json` checked into the ticket folder records prior runs; the `transcript.md` summarises each run for continuation.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nWhen a `tdf/<key>` PR you opened is merged, `.github/workflows/jira-pr-merged.yml` finalizes things (transitions Jira to Done, deletes the head branch). Do not try to do that yourself.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nYour job on each run:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n1. Read the generated ticket artefacts, especially the spec file referenced by `SPEC_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n2. Write or update the implementation plan at the exact path in `PLAN_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n3. Implement only the requested ticket work on the current branch.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n4. Write the Jira-facing summary or answer to `RESPONSE_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n5. Keep generated ticket artefacts organised under `spec/<TICKET-ID>/` and avoid cluttering the repository root.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n6. Leave pull request creation, branch pushes, and Jira commenting to the workflow.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Dispatch Flow Context\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nWhen the dispatch flow runs, the workflow exports these env vars before invoking you:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `ISSUE_KEY`, `ISSUE_TITLE`, `JIRA_ISSUE_URL`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `KIND`: `pr` (expects code changes plus a PR) or `answer` (expects only ticket-folder updates and a Jira-facing response)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `IS_NEW`: `true` if this is the first run for the ticket, `false` if continuing\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `LAST_SESSION_ID`: prior Codex session id, when known (currently informational; resume is not auto-wired)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- `TICKET_FOLDER` (e.g. `spec/KAN-1`), `STATE_FILE`, `TRANSCRIPT_FILE`, `SPEC_FILE`, `PLAN_FILE`, `RESPONSE_FILE`, `RUN_DIR`\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n`KIND` is determined from Jira:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Label `claude:answer` → `answer` (highest priority).\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Label `claude:pr` → `pr`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Issue type `Question` → `answer`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Default → `pr`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n(Label names retain the `claude:` prefix for backward compatibility with Jira automation rules; semantically they map to \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"answer mode\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" / \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"PR mode\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" regardless of the underlying agent.)\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nIf `KIND=answer`, do not edit any file outside `TICKET_FOLDER`. Write the full answer to `RESPONSE_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nIf `KIND=pr`, make minimal correct repository changes, update `PLAN_FILE`, and write a short Jira-facing summary to `RESPONSE_FILE`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Operating Context\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- The branch name normally starts with a Jira key, often lowercased by Jira automation. The dispatch flow uses `tdf/<ticket-id-lowercase>` for PR mode.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- The workflow normalises Jira keys before generating ticket artefact paths.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- The current branch is the work branch. Do not switch branches.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Do not merge pull requests, close tickets, or edit Jira directly unless the ticket explicitly asks for that behaviour and the workflow provides the required tools.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Prefer small, direct changes that match the ticket acceptance criteria.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Model Use\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nThe default Codex model is whatever the runner's `~/.codex/config.toml` selects (typically `gpt-5.5` at medium reasoning effort). The workflow does not pin a specific model or effort yet; if a ticket calls for higher reasoning effort, request it in the spec or via a follow-up tweak to `.github/workflows/jira-dispatch.yml`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nUse cheaper / faster modes when the subtask doesn't need full reasoning:\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- searching for files or symbols\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- summarizing long logs\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- checking formatting or simple syntax issues\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- drafting routine markdown\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- performing narrow mechanical edits\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\nReserve high-effort reasoning for architecture, workflow design, security-sensitive logic, ambiguous requirements, and final review before handing work back to the workflow.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n## Quality Bar\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Prefer real repository state over assumptions.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Validate changed scripts with syntax checks when possible.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- If a web page or HTML artifact is created, ensure it can render in a browser and mention any unverified visual risk in the plan.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n- Do not commit transient Codex execution files such as `events.jsonl`, `last_message.txt`, or `output.txt` outside `RUN_DIR`.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"exit_code\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":0,\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"status\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"completed\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"}}\\\\\\\\n./spec/KAN-3/runs/20260509T132123Z-25602124761/events.jsonl:11:{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"type\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"item.completed\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"item\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"id\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"item_4\\\\\